It&#x27;s called a jump table or vtable.<p>It&#x27;s one of the examples in Forth. Plan 9 uses that technique in C a lot too.<p>This example is ramfs which creates an in memory file system (that you can mount in Unix btw, in 166 LoC)<p><a href="http://swtch.com/usr/local/plan9/src/lib9p/ramfs.c" rel="nofollow">http://swtch.com/usr/local/plan9/src/lib9p/ramfs.c</a><p>fsopen, fsread, fswrite, fscreate are C functions declared in the same source file :<p><pre><code>    Srv fs = {
	.open=	fsopen,
	.read=	fsread,
	.write=	fswrite,
	.create=	fscreate,
    };

</code></pre>
fs is then passed to a library which calls them as needed.
